{
  "texts": [
    "4 and the corresponding substitution analysis).",
    "This empirical approach has the advantage of offering a specific, measurable criterion for determining whether or not LLM-generated norms are suitable.",
    "However, a disadvantage is that it does not contend with theoretical objections whether an LLM is in principle capable of providing certain kinds of judgments.",
    "The other approach is conceptual and focuses on questions of a priori validity: given the limitations of their training data (e.g., solely linguistic input), then LLMs can perhaps be relied upon for judgments about language, but not judgments about the world or human society.",
    "This objection could be analogized to the question of face validity: there are certain theoretical constructs for which LLM-generated judgments simply seem implausible or inherently unreliable (e.g., perhaps moral norms)."
  ]
}